                    },
                    "comments": [
                        {
                            "type": {
                                "id": 201,
                                "en": "On-site releases comment",
                                "fr": "Commentaire sur les rejets sur le site"
                            },
                            "comment": "In 2021, Northstone decommissioned three of its existing four 3MW Cooper Bessemer LSV16 Reciprocating Engines. The decision to decommission comes from rising operating costs of these units, as they are much less efficient, and rising carbon prices have made them non-economical. That being said, production and total emissions have increased by more than 10 percent from the previous year due to a number of factors. The impact of Covid-19 on the Alberta electricity demand and market in 2020/2021, along with changing market factors such as pool price, natural gas prices, and renewable energy sources entering the market, have played a big role in day to day business operating decisions. The nature of Northstone's business is reacting to the market, so this change is expected and not an anomaly. Northstone had much higher production, generally because pool prices were higher in 2021. Because Northstone had higher production, there was also an increase in Nitrogen Oxide emissions."
                        }
                    ],
